observations.recommendation:
In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the City Mayor require the: 

PCLSB to – 

Provide an assessment or detailed timeline on when the said facilities will be fully operational and consider all necessary steps for the immediate implementation of these projects; 

Consider proper timing of construction at all times in the procurement planning to maximize the service potential of the STP facilities and to forestall additional costs brought about by possible damage that may be sustained while waiting for the availability of the electrical supply;

Conduct pre-operational activities in all its future projects to consider all the necessary requirements of project implementation to avoid any delays;

OCA and the CEO to coordinate in conducting ocular inspection of completed infrastructure assets, buildings and other structures and thereafter, evaluate whether assets are available for use as intended for proper recording in the books of accounts in accordance with Item No. 71 of IPSAS 17.

We recommended that the City Mayor advise the:
City Accountant to -
Review the amount of P29,076,469.45 appearing as unremitted and cause the immediate remittance to the GSIS, Pag-IBIG, and PhilHealth;
Remit the withheld amounts of mandatory counterpart and premium contributions of the City within the prescribed period to avoid penalties and to guarantee that City personnel/employees enjoy the full benefits from the GSIS, Pag-IBIG, and PhilHealth;
Ensure that the remittances correspond to the exact amounts withheld;
Coordinate with the HRMD Office for the timely submission of payrolls for the computation of the exact amount of contributions withheld due for remittance; and
HRMD Officer to exert earnest efforts to reconcile its record of personnel with GSIS; and
City Accountant and the HRMD Officer to continue close coordination to further address the issues noted in the preparation of payrolls and remittances.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the City Mayor direct the:

a. OCA to –

•	Strictly enforce the liquidation of CAs granted to AOs within the reglementary period;


•	Send demand letters to all erring AOs who are still active in the service and to submit their names to the CLO for appropriate action including the immediate withholding of salaries and other unpaid claims due to them; 

b. OCLO to recommend to the City Mayor, the appropriate action to recover the unliquidated CAs from the AOs who were already separated from the service;

c. City Administrator to constantly remind concerned officials and employees on the pertinent laws, rules and regulations governing the handling of CA every time they are granted with; and

d. OCT to remind the SDO to submit immediately the liquidation report including the official receipt as proof of refund of the unused CAs to ensure the full liquidation.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the City Mayor direct the City Treasurer to: 

Religiously monitor the collections and remittances to ensure that all FSIF collected on behalf of BFP are remitted promptly to the latter;

Send confirmation letter to the PCFS and reconcile it with the balance per accounting records to ascertain the correct amount due for remittance;

Communicate with the OCA the needs for adjustment of the amount recorded in the books subject for remittance, if any;

Remit immediately the outstanding FSIF to the BFP identified as the result of confirmation and reconciliation; and 

Ensure that the amount remitted during the month corresponds to the amount collected for FSIF on behalf of the BFP.

We recommended that the OCA:

Ensure the timely recording of the transactions and remittance of correct amount of taxes withheld to avoid the surcharges, interests and penalties provided under Section 247 (b), Title X of the National Internal Revenue Code (NIRC) of 1997 and Revenue Memorandum Circular (RMC) No. 23-2007;


Coordinate with the HRMDO for the timely submission of payrolls for the computation of the exact amount of taxes withheld due for remittance.

We recommended the City Mayor to direct the City Health Officer to:
a. Consider the remaining stocks available prior to procuring drugs and medicines specifically those slow-moving items to avoid the overstocking of inventory through determination of stock in their next procurement level/reorder point which should include calculation of average monthly distribution and lead times for items requisition and observance of procurement of inventories within the normal requirements of city health centers;
b. Closely monitor the stock level of inventory and identify those slow-moving inventories that need not be procured on a quarterly basis to avoid possible expiration and long storage of overstock drugs and medicines.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the City Mayor require the:
a. PCLSB to –
• Provide an assessment or detailed timeline on when the said facilities will be fully operational and consider all necessary steps for the immediate implementation of these projects;
• Consider proper timing of construction at all times in the procurement planning to maximize the service potential of the STP facilities and to forestall additional costs brought about by possible damage that may be sustained while waiting for the availability of the electrical supply; and
• Conduct pre-operational activities in all its future projects to consider all the necessary requirements of project implementation to avoid any delays;

We recommended that the City Mayor require the:
a. GSO to ensure that the AIR and other supporting documents are submitted immediately to the OCA for timely recording of receipt of deliveries and issuance of inventory items by OCA;
b. OCA to effect the necessary accounting entries to adjust the balances of the affected accounts.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the:
a. City Assessor to –
• Ensure that Assessment Levels and Assessed Values are accurately computed/provided to generate the correct assessed values and real property and special education taxes;
• Submit to the Audit Group the updated copies of Tax Declaration as proof of corrections/updates made to the 10 RPUs;

We recommended that the CGSO –
a. Maintain updated Stock Cards for each inventory item to serve as the basis of reconciliation in the conduct and preparation of the RPCI;
b. Prepare the required inventory forms accurately with complete information to facilitate recording and reconciliation of inventory items;
c. Ensure the preparation of the SAI and completeness of supporting documents in the issuance of inventories; and
d. Prepare and consistently submit weekly the SSMI, duly supported with RIS pertaining to the issuances of inventories.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the:
City Health Officer to submit written justification for the delay in the submission of the SOA and the Lists of Patient-beneficiaries to the City Accountant;
City Accountant to –
Inform the PRC on the names of patients that appeared twice in the list while only 648 patients matched with the referral Lists of the CHO costing P2,268,000.00 was considered liquidated and to submit additional supporting documents for the unliquidated portion of P5.00 million, if any;
Take up the necessary entries to adjust the balances of accounts affected by the amount of liquidation of P2,268,000.00; and
Henceforth, strictly comply and implement the provisions of COA Circular No. 2007-001 dated October 25, 2007.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the:
City Administrator to –
Rescind the Contracts of Lease (CL) of the delinquent stallholders and not to renew the CL of those with records of delinquency;
Cancel the CL of the stallholders who failed to pay the rental fees for three consecutive months and thereafter, declare the stall vacant without prejudice to suing the lessee for the unpaid rents at the expenses of the lessee pursuant to Section 21 of the PCMC;
Closely monitor and supervise the operation and management of the PCPM and take the necessary appropriate action for any violations by stallholders on the terms and conditions in their Contracts of Lease and of the PCMC;
City Treasurer to -
Regularly monitor the collections of rental, electricity and water consumption fees at any given period to ensure these are promptly collected; and
Direct the Administrative Officer, Market Section, OCT and market collectors to exert more effort to collect the outstanding dues totaling P18,600,248.65.

We recommended that the City Mayor advise the City Treasurer to:
Ensure that the computation of RPT and SET is accurate pursuant to Sections 19 and 20 of the Ordinance No. 240, s. 1993;
Undertake immediately the corrections on RPUs with erroneous computation of RPT and SET;
Collect the taxes that were under collected from the period that these became due to avoid the issuance of the Notice of Charge to persons who caused the under assessment/billing of real property taxes;
Investigate the reasons or causes of under computation of RPT and SET, considering that the City uses the Real Property Assessment System, wherein taxes are supposed to be automatically computed since the data from the Assessment are synchronized/linked to the Billing and Collection modules; and
Enable the Real Property Assessment System to automatically compute for the RPT and SET with the conditions/parameters compliant with Sections 19 and 20 of the Ordinance.

We recommended that the City Mayor advise the City Treasurer to –
Include the taxable 42 RPUs in the RPTRR and provide computation of RPT and SET collectible for the year;
Ensure that all taxable RPUs in the AR are included in the RPTRR;
Submit explanation on the inclusion of the 20 RPUs in the RPTRR despite that the same were not found in the AR;
Indicate in the RPTRR the classification/actual use of the taxable properties to ensure that the computation of RPT and SET is accurate;
Make the necessary corrections on the rates applied to the 44 residential and 11 commercial RPUs;
Ascertain that rates applied to taxable RPUs are correct;
City Assessor to –
verify the MV of RPUs not included in the AR and inform the City Treasurer on the amount of AVs as their basis in the RPTRR;
Exclude the tax-exempt RPUs in the AR for taxable RPUs and include them in the AR for tax-exempt RPUs in accordance with Section 3 Chapter V (Assessment of Real Property), Manual on Real Property Appraisal and Assessment Operations; and
The City Treasurer and City Assessor to reconcile their records to produce reliable reports as basis in the computation of RPT and SET.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the:
City Accountant to-
Review the amount appearing as unremitted and cause the immediate remittance to the GSIS and PhilHealth, and take up the necessary adjustments to correct the amount in the case of Pag-IBIG;
Ensure that the remittances correspond to the exact amount withheld;
Remit the withheld amounts of mandatory counterparts and premium contributions of the City, within the prescribed period to avoid penalties and to guarantee that City personnel/employees enjoy the full benefits from the GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth;
HRMD Officer to-
Set a reasonable deadline for the timely submission of the DTRs to prevent delay in the preparation of the payrolls including supporting documents for indorsement to the OCA necessary to record the contributions withheld as basis for remittance;
Immediately update the member’s profiles in case of any changes in the employment status using the ARA; and
City Accountant and the HRMD Officer to continue close coordination to further address the issues noted in the preparation of payrolls and remittances.

observations.managementAction:
The City has already accomplished the following:

Enacted Ordinance No. 5891 calling for the creation of the PDAO;

Appropriated P2.829 million for its operations;

Conducted General Assembly last April 29, 2019 which was attended by 127 PWDs; and

Convened to tackle the vacant positions under PDAO.

observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the OCA to:
Set up an effective review level so as to detect errors, inaccuracies and oversight in the accounting process, like the completeness of agency assets that are subjected to depreciation, the accuracy of information used, and the computation of depreciation and amortization;
Prepare an accurate Schedule of PPE and Intangible Assets to facilitate the correct computation of the Carrying amounts of PPE and IAs, Depreciation Expenses and Amortization;
Observe the PAG 3 to IPSAS 17 in the initial recognition of Depreciation of PPE;
Stop depreciating items that are already beyond their useful lives; and
Effect the necessary adjustments.

We recommended that the OCA to:
Set up an effective review level so as to detect errors, inaccuracies and oversight in the accounting process, like the completeness of agency assets that are subjected to depreciation, the accuracy of information used, and the computation of depreciation and amortization;
Prepare an accurate Schedule of PPE and Intangible Assets to facilitate the correct computation of the Carrying amounts of PPE and IAs, Depreciation Expenses and Amortization;
Observe the PAG 3 to IPSAS 17 in the initial recognition of Depreciation of PPE;
Stop depreciating items that are already beyond their useful lives, and
Effect the necessary adjustments.

We recommended the following:
The PCLSB to –
Ensure that only allowable expenses are included as items of expenditures in the preparation and formulation of the budget by observing the pertinent provisions of the DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, Series of 2017;
Abandon the projects for implementation which are not allowed to be charged against the SEF under the JC; and
Make representations with the City to allot funds available for the settlement of ineligible expenses charged against the SEF amounting to P90,023,309.92 for CY 2019;
The City appropriate funds in the amount of P90,023,309.92 in the GF to cover the expenses disbursed for ineligible items charged against the SEF;
Management charge P90,023,309.92 paid for the ineligible expenses against the GF and transfer the amount to the SEF; and
The City Accountant to ascertain, during its pre-audit activities, that all payments made out of SEF are strictly for allowable expenses only as enumerated under Section 4 of the JC.

We recommended that:
a. The OCA –
Review the amount appearing as unremitted, cause the immediate remittance to the GSIS and PhilHealth, and record the correct credit amount in the case of Pag-IBIG;
Ensure that the remittances correspond to the exact amount withheld;
Remit the withheld amounts of mandatory counterpart and premium contributions of the City, as well as loan repayments, within the prescribed period to avoid penalties and to guarantee that City personnel/employees enjoy the full benefits from the GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth;
Revisit the existing procedures with the end view of addressing the noted observations; and
Strictly comply with Section 6 (b) of RA No. 8291 or the GSIS Act, Rule VII of the IRR of RA No. 9679 or the HDMF Law or Pag-IBIG Fund, and PhilHealth Advisory No. 0404-04-2014 and Section 11 of Title III Rule II of the RIRR of the National Health Insurance Act of 2013, together with the guidelines and instructions set forth therein to avoid payment of unnecessary penalties on the unremitted amounts.
b. The HRMDO to set a reasonable deadline and strictly implement the timely submission of the DTRs of each employee to prevent delay of preparation of the payroll and submit the payroll on time to the OCA for timely recording of the contributions withheld as basis of remittance to be made; and
c. The OCA and the HRMDO to continue their close coordination to further address the issues noted in the preparation of payrolls and remittances.
We also recommended that the City push through with its negotiations with the AGDB in the use of the ATM facility for the payroll of all casual and contractual employees.

observations.managementAction:
PCCWC shall continuously –

Endeavor to consider the whole system and areas of concern provided under the law in identifying the programs, projects and activities to be undertaken for the City, to ensure achievements of the target results at the level of the LGU in contributing to the successful implementation of the law;

Come up with the PPAs that are aligned and complementary to the regular programs and projects of the City in order to avoid redundancy and non-implementation of lined-up PPAs;

Ensure that the proposed are supported with thorough studies and plans, with due consideration of existing PPAs of other offices of the City, in order to establish their viability and implementation for the attainment of the objectives of the law; and

Establish proper coordination with concerned offices to deter delays or hindrances in the implementation of projects.

observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management require:
The OCA to -
Strictly enforce the liquidation of CAs granted to AOs within the reglementary period and the immediate refund of unspent amounts;
Continue sending demand letters to all erring AOs who are still active in the service and to submit their names to the CLO for appropriate action including the immediate withholding of salaries and other unpaid claims due them;
Re-file the request for write-off strictly following the requirements of COA Circular No. 2016-005;
The CLO to recommend to the City Mayor appropriate action to be taken for AOs who are already separated from the service; and
The City Administrator to constantly remind concerned officials and employees on the pertinent laws, rules and regulations governing the handling of cash advance every time they are granted with cash advance.

We recommended that:
The BPLO and CTO -
Conduct simultaneous and coordinated inspection of businesses that did not renew their business/mayor’s permits and exercise the rights and remedies of the City pursuant to Sections 102 and 103 of the Pasay City Revenue Code;
Consider enhancement of the present computerized system to provide facility of generating a report of business establishments with history details of renewal of registration, payment of business permits, fees and applicable taxes;
The CTO design and implement effective collection strategies that will intensify collection efficiency of the City as regards business permits;
The BPLO -
Refrain from issuing Mayor’s Permit without the clearance issued by the barangays out of the City’s program of ‘ease of doing business; and
Strictly enforce the requirement on the submission of barangay clearances before Mayor’s Permits are granted.

We reiterate our previous recommendations that Management require:
The CTO -
Collect the underpayment of business taxes from the owners of the concerned establishments, inclusive of interests and surcharges, as necessary;
Issue an order cancelling the license to operate of concerned establishments, in case of non-settlement of the business tax delinquencies, if warranted;
The CTO and BPLO to exercise its authority to inspect/examine the books of accounts of the concerned suppliers, service providers and contractors, pursuant to Section 171 of RA No. 7160; and
The BPLO to submit the relevant details pertaining to the remaining six suppliers, service providers or contractors who participated and won in the public bidding and contracted with the City in CY 2017, for evaluation.

We recommended that Management:
Revise the revenue Ordinances to consider all provisions of the Local Government Code on the imposition and collection as well as the general administrative provisions on taxation to ensure complete coverage, applicability and clarity of provisions of the revenue Ordinances, including imposition of interests and other surcharges. On the other hand, review existing provisions of the revenue Ordinances which are not aligned or not covered by the Code;
Update the rates and amounts of taxes to reflect the prevailing cost of taxation and be responsive to the current times and circumstances;
Study new and emerging businesses that are not previously mentioned in the Ordinances presently implemented and provisions that extend beyond the territorial limits of the City for inclusion in the revision of the proposed legislation; and
Cause the codification of the revenue rules to facilitate its usage as reference of the City officials and employees as well as the taxpayers and other stakeholders.

We recommended that:
The CGSO -
Maintain updated Stock Cards for each inventory item to serve as basis of reconciliation in the conduct and preparation of the RPCI;
Prepare the required inventory forms accurately with complete information to facilitate recording and reconciliation of inventory items;
Ensure the preparation of the SAI and completeness of supporting documents in the issuance of inventories;
Prepare and consistently submit weekly the SSMI, duly supported with RIS pertaining to the issuances of inventories; and
The OCA maintain updated SLCs that would support the balances of the inventory accounts and ensure that recorded issuances of inventories are duly supported with properly accomplished SSMI.

We recommended that:
The OCA -
Review the amounts appearing as unremitted and cause the immediate remittance to the GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth;
Ensure that the remittances correspond to the exact amount withheld;
Remit the withheld amounts of mandatory counterpart and premium contributions of the City, as well as loan repayments, within the prescribed period to avoid penalties and to guarantee that the City personnel/employees enjoy the full benefits from the GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth;
Revisit the existing procedures with the end view of addressing the noted observations;
Strictly comply with the provisions of Section 6 (b) of RA 8291 or the GSIS Act, Rule VII of the IRR of RA No. 9679 or the HDMF Law or Pag-IBIG Fund, and PhilHealth Advisory No. 0404-04-2014 and Section 11 of Title III Rule II of the RIRR of the National Health Insurance Act of 2013, together with the guidelines and instructions set forth therein to avoid payment of unnecessary penalties on the unremitted amounts;
The HRMDO set a reasonable deadline and strictly implement the timely submission of the DTRs of each employee to prevent delay in the preparation of the payroll and submit the payroll on time to the OCA for timely recording of the contributions withheld as basis of the remittance to be made; and
The OCA and the HRMDO closely coordinate to further address the issues noted in the preparation of payrolls and remittances.

We recommended that the PCCWC:
Properly evaluate/study/screen project proposals in all aspects before approval, and carefully identify the applicable needed resources to carry out the project, in order to establish their viability and implementation;
Consider the provision of contingencies for price increases in the project proposal;
Carefully review items to be procured using the LCPC funds in the implementation of PPAs, which could be possibly co-funded with the general fund of the City;
Champion the conduct of scheduled meetings of the Council and the committee/sub-committees, and require the submission of committee/sub-committee reports to ensure appropriate and timely action on concerns reported regarding the implementation of approved PPAs; and
Secure the commitment of offices/agencies concerned in their participation/involvement in the implementation of the PPAs to deter delays or hindrances in carrying out the projects.

We recommended the following:
The OCA issue demand letters to all concerned City employees with unliquidated cash advances and cause the withholding of their salaries or other claims due them for the settlement of the unliquidated amounts pursuant to Section 5.9 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
As regards AOs who have already retired, resigned or transferred to other agencies, the OCA submits their cases to the CLO for appropriate legal remedies;
The Management put in place an effective mechanism to constantly remind all AOs of the pertinent laws, rules and regulations governing the handling of cash advances before their release in order to preclude the ballooning of unliquidated amounts;
The Management initiate action to request the write-off of the dormant cash advances following the requirements and procedures provided under COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016. Moreover, the OCA reclassify the shortage of P970,382.42 of  the former Cashier as Due from Officers and Employees; and
The OCA observe appropriate timing in granting Cash Advances for special purpose and install control measure to prevent the drawing of Cash Advances at a very advanced period prior to the intended use, in order to avoid exposing funds to the risk of theft, loss or misuse.
The City Accountant in her letter dated April 16, 2018 commented that the OCA:
Shall continuously issue the corresponding demand letters and submission of the cases to the City Legal Office for appropriate legal remedies;
Make the necessary request to initiate the writing off process of the dormant cash advances and shall reclassify the account of Ms. Raffols; and
Has put in place the necessary mechanisms to cause the due utilization and liquidation of the cash advances, and that the delays in liquidation are due to factors that are beyond the control of the OCA.
The Management commented that the cases of the AOs who have retired, resigned and transferred were already endorsed to the Office of the Ombudsman, and pending resolution therein.

We recommended that the City Accountant  to:

Reconcile, analyze and investigate further the discrepancy noted between the book balances and the RPCPPE balances and make adjustments where appropriate;




Provide depreciation for the completed projects  over their useful life by considering the change in the estimated residual value to 5 percent of the cost in accordance with PPSAS from the 10 per cent under the old NGAS, for accurate presentation of depreciation expense and the accumulated depreciation of the subject PPE in the financial statements; 

Analyze further the CIP-Buildings and Other Structures account and reconcile the posting of payments in the IP which were not recorded in the CIP account and other PPE accounts and identify the source  document of the reference number as basis in posting the payments in the IP; and 

Review the CIP account for the non-moving balances and take up the necessary adjustment in the books.

We recommended and Management agreed that the City Accountant to:

Analyze and prepare journal entries for the identified book reconciling items reflected in the bank reconciliation and the same be done before closing the books to ensure the accuracy of the cash at the end of each reporting period;



Reconcile the different balances of the general ledger and subsidiary ledger and ensure that the person responsible for recording and posting transactions in the book exercise prudent and due care in carrying out his/her duties and responsibilities;

Continue the gathering of documents for analysis and reconciliation and to trace the accounting entries made in previous years starting on the set up of the PNB-Makati account and the recorded series of transactions that occurred to determine the non-existence of the account per confirmed zero balance;



Identify related account/s that were affected. As such, this action to be made by the City Accountant is seen to be the only recourse to cleanse the City’s books of the non-existing cash in bank; 

Reconcile the bank and book balances at all times; and



Revert back to the CIB-LCCA and the appropriate liability accounts checks that remained outstanding for more than six months as of year-end.

We recommended that:

The City Accountant and City Assessor reconcile the difference of the recorded RPT receivables and the delinquent accounts as reflected in the List of Delinquencies per RPTAS;



The  City Assessor to assign new ARP numbers to the identified 92 pairs of property with identical ARP numbers;





The City Treasurer to determine if payments made by one of the property are likewise applied to the other property to which it shared identical ARP number. If there is such occurrence, reassess and collect the same from the delinquent taxpayer; and 

The City Assessor and the City Treasurer to inform COA of the action taken.

We recommended that Management direct:

The General Services Officer to submit the SSMIs on a weekly basis and to conduct a physical count of inventories semestrally;

The Chief Accountant to maintain SLCs.


The Chief Accountant and the General Services Officer:

undertake an inventory reconciliation process, the result of the said undertaking should be made the basis of Management’s subsequent actions in correcting the inventory accounts;



adopt fully the Perpetual Inventory Method by recording all purchases to the inventory accounts and record issuances only when supported with RISs receipted by the actual end-user;

We recommended the Management to:

Formulate internal guidelines/procedures for the determination of amount to be given to Public Health Workers and Public Social Workers based on the nature of services rendered and degree of exposures, to ensure propriety and reasonableness of the amounts granted to them;

Require the OCA and OCT to stop the payment of Magna Carta benefits to employees without an express authority from the City Mayor (CM) and require them to refund the amounts illegally received earlier and ensure that all payrolls should be supported with DTRs, approved assignment orders and detailed report of activities;

Identify those employees who should be entitled to subsistence allowance in accordance with Section 8.2.1 of the IRR of R. A. 9433.

We have recommended that Management require the City Treasurer to:
Reconcile the RPT Receivable accounts with the List of Delinquent Taxpayers; Submit to COA the completed List of Delinquent Taxpayers as of CY 2015; and;
Prepare and send demand letters for the payment of tax arrears and corresponding penalties, interests and surcharges. Provide COA with duly authenticated copies of all demand letters sent to the said GOCCs.
